  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 염립본(閻立本)이 …… 것 : '
    value: 염립본(閻立本)은 당나라의 유명한 화가(畵家)이다. 당 태종(唐太宗)이 신하들과 함께 춘원지(春苑池)에서 배를 타고 노는데 기이한 새가 물 위에 놀고 있었다. 태종이 입본을 불러서 그것을 그리게 하였더니, 내시가, “화사(畵師)는 속히 들라.” 하고 외치었다. 입본이 이때에 벼슬이 벌써 주작낭중(主爵郞中)에 이르렀는데, 연못가에 엎드려서 물감을 입에 빨며 그림을 그리고 있는 다른 사람들을 바라보고는 부끄러워 땀이 흘렀다. 집에 돌아와서 자손에게 경계하기를 “내가 글을 읽어서 문장이 남보다 못하지 않은데, 지금 그림 그리는 재주 때문에 천한 화사(畵師) 노릇을 하였으니, 너희들은 그림을 배우지 말라. 그러나 나는 성질이 그림을 좋아하므로 그만둘 수도 없다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 중니(仲尼)가 …… 좇았으나 : '
    value: 공자가 노(魯)나라에 살 때에 사람들이 사냥하여 서로 승부를 비교하는 풍습이 있었는데, 이것을 엽각(獵較)라 하였다. 공자도 남이 하는 대로 따라서 참가하였다. 이것은 한(漢)나라 동중서(董仲舒)의 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 오패(五覇) : '
    value: 오패(五覇)는 제 환공(齊桓公)ㆍ진 문공(晉文公)ㆍ진 목공(秦穆公)ㆍ송 양공(宋襄公)ㆍ초 장왕(楚莊王) 등이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 군자가 …… 의 : '
    value: 군자는 사람을 덕으로써 사랑한다는 말이 있다. 그것은 남을 사랑하려면 옳은 사람이 되도록 인도하여 주어야 한다는 뜻이다. 《禮記》
english:
  title: Reply to Lee Jung-pyeong's Letter
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your gracious letter arrived bearing wisdom that illuminates like dawn breaking through long darkness. How could my heart not overflow with gratitude? Yet when you praise my humble brushwork—comparing orchids to snow-framed clarity, bamboo to the lover of antiquity—such excessive praise burdens me. But as the old saying goes, when the blind man of Guangtong condemns divination, fortune reverses itself. Yet divination determines fortune and misfortune. How then can words contradict their own principle? The blind possess no fixed knowledge; thus fortune and misfortune become reversed. The world, observing this paradox, treats it as divination itself—though it is divination by one who knows not divination.

    I have heard it said: when people call the old man a person, people deem it right; when they call him not a person, people deem it wrong. Thus praise and blame have no fixed dwelling—they depend entirely on how one praises and how one blames. After merely weeks of wielding brush, I suddenly find myself recipient of Guangtong's praise. Can one remain unmoved by such inconsistency?

    Your letter deeply reproaches my study of painting, citing Yan Liben's shame at being summoned as a mere painter, and Zhao Mengfu's virtue obscured by his art. Yet I confess I feel no particular shame. Though all may practice the same art, their intentions differ. The gentleman finds art a vehicle for meaning; the small man devotes his entire mind to technique alone. Those who exhaust themselves in technique are like craftsmen and laborers who sell their skill for sustenance. Those who lodge their spirit in art are like refined and cultured scholars who probe the mysteries of principle.

    Confucius was a sage yet capable of menial tasks; Hsi K'ang, a man of understanding, loved metalwork. Did they devote their minds to these things and thereby corrupt themselves? You treat all matters as equal—much like Guangtong's talk of fortune. How can such reasoning command belief?

    Moreover, among all things that delight the human spirit without moving it away from its purpose, none surpass writing and painting. When the gentleman, having exhausted himself in clarifying virtue and principle, finds spirit weary and body spent, unable to practice archery or horsemanship, unable to play the zither or lute—what then shall nurture his spirit and cultivate his nature? But when one sits at desk and table, brush in hand upon paper, quietly observing the ten thousand things, discerning differences minute as hair's breadth, rendering form through hand's movement—is this not the universe within my palm? Every grass, every flower perceived by eye and comprehended by heart, then flowing through hand to become image—when one brushstroke captures the spiritual, it mirrors heaven's mechanism; when one brushstroke achieves subtlety, it echoes heaven's workings. Thus wielding brush and ink, one perpetually plays with heaven's design. How vastly different from those worldly ones who expand their courtyards, gather flowers and strange stones, arrange them left and right, boasting of wealth and splendor!

    As for Yan Liben displaying his skill before his sovereign—this brought no shame. That the palace attendant mistakenly summoned him as a mere craftsman—any man of true measure would laugh it off. Why should he later warn his descendants with regret and sorrow? This reveals that Liben possessed no other virtue to overshadow his technical skill. Zhao Mengfu's virtue and literary brilliance shine clearly in the historical record; that his biography became eclipsed by his painting owes merely to the eulogist's rhetoric of elevation and depression. Should one doubt his virtue's completeness on this account, one does not truly know Mengfu.

    Yet your letter claims that studying painting yields merely the appointment to direct the painting academy, gaining perhaps one or two minor officials. Though your words show clever tongue, this is not how one addresses a gentleman. If a gentleman must depend on technique and expect material reward, did not Confucius follow hunting competitions? Yet we hear not that he became master of the hunt. Did not Tseng Tien play the zither? Yet we hear not that he became a court musician. In our own age, those called sages sometimes cultivate flowers and become captivated by them. Yet would one expect such cultivation to secure appointment as overseer of the imperial gardens, receiving honors for withered fruit?

    Yet your letter also says: "In leisure from farming, attend to the classics and histories; thus your influence might reach heaven and earth, assisting in creation itself." These words hold truth indeed, and your concern is not shallow. But men change—three days' separation brings new growth to the eye that truly sees. How do you know that since we parted, I have not come to understand the Six Classics and master the historians?

    Confucius taught: "Ground yourself on virtue, rely upon humanity, and find leisure in the arts." The commentators explain: leisure means to observe things and accord with one's nature. The arts are the Six Arts; painting belongs to the category of writing, itself one of the Six Arts. When the gentleman first establishes the foundation of virtue and principle, then extends into the application of the Six Arts—what harm comes to him? If technique and the arts opposed virtue and righteousness as ice opposes flame, Confucius would have forbidden them entirely, not taught that one should ground oneself on virtue and rely on humanity before finding leisure in the arts.

    Consider a certain villager who, seeing someone finish eating and drink tea, rushes forward crying: "This harms your original vital force! You must not consume it!" The person merely laughs and continues drinking. The villager, angered at being ignored, calls throughout the village: "That man shall surely fall ill!" Yet the person, nourished by the meal, grows stronger and more vigorous. The villager knew not that tea's nature purges filth and corruption, unsuitable for the empty-bellied but most beneficial for the full. If one fails to investigate whether virtue and principle are empty or full, treating all technique and art as external things to be rejected—is this not to become like that villager?

    Your letter contains some hundreds of phrases, yet none ring true, nothing worthy of consideration. My rough words and blind observations may offend—will you permit them? A gentleman's speech must above all be sincere; one must not employ cunning deceptions. To speak without sincerity while deceiving through artifice is called deception. To harbor false intent while cloaking it in fair words is called fraud. In Confucius's school, even a child of five feet tall was ashamed to speak of the Five Hegemons, for they placed deception before benevolence and righteousness. Unless deception and fraud are purged, all fall away from Confucius.

    Observing your intent, your essential desire is to recover your ink bamboo painting. Your approach merely wraps this in pretty words: "Return my ancient painting." But you begin with false emotion and empty praise to gladden my heart, continue by attacking the principles of painting to unsettle me, and end by subtly revealing your true longing, hoping I might return it. Your thousand words and myriad phrases employ nothing but cunning artifice to deceive. Should I comply, you would surely say: "Only clever deception succeeds in this world!" Thus I would merely compound my fault. This contradicts the gentleman's way of loving others through virtue.

    If you had simply and straightforwardly requested its return, what was easily obtained before could easily be returned now. Otherwise, I should cast it into water and fire as punishment for your love of cunning stratagems. Consider this well. I bow in reply.
  footnotes:
    - Yan Liben was a renowned Tang dynasty painter. When Emperor Taizong saw a rare bird on Spring Garden Pond, he summoned Yan Liben to paint it. As court attendants shouted 'Summon the painter!' Liben, already risen to the rank of Court Steward, found himself crawling by the water's edge mixing pigments with his mouth while observing other painters. Ashamed and sweating, he later warned his descendants never to study painting, though his nature compelled him to continue.
    - When Confucius lived in Lu, there was a custom called 'hunting competition' where people hunted and compared results. Confucius participated like others.
    - The Five Hegemons were the rulers of Qi, Jin, Qin, Song, and Chu during the Zhou dynasty.
    - The gentleman loves others through virtue—meaning one should guide others to become righteous persons rather than employing cunning means.
